Concepts and Critical Thinking

Question 1

Describe, in your own words, what the marginal rate of technical substitution means. How is it different from the slope of the isocost line?

The marginal rate of technical substitution (MRST) is the tradeoff (or exchange rate) between two inputs for a firm (based on its technology or production function). The number literally means the amount of capital the firm would remove (rate of substitution) if they were to use 1 more unit of labor to produce the same amount of output.

The \(MRTS=\frac{MP_l}{MP_k}\) is the slope of the isoquant curves, which expresses all the combinations of \(l\) and \(k\) that produce the same output \(q\).

The slope of the isocost line \(\frac{w}{r}\) is the rate at which the market trades off (or the exchange rate) between \(l\) and \(k\), based on relative factor prices.

Question 2

Describe, in your own words, what is true at the least-cost input combination (the optimum) for a firm. Why is it the optimum? What does the equality of the slope of the isoquant curve and the slope of the isocost line mean, in English?

At the optimum point, the producer minimizes their total cost (reaches the lowest possible isocost line) for a given level of output (a given isoquant curve) â€“ thus their optimum is at a point where the two are tangent. At a tangency, the slopes between the budget constraint and the indifference curve are the same. We have seen that at this point: \[\frac{MP_l}{w}=\frac{MP_k}{r}\]

This means that at the optimum, the marginal product (output gained) for every dollar spent on either labor or capital is the same. That is, you can get no more output by spending a dollar more on labor, or by spending a dollar more on capital. This combination is the best that you can possibly do.

Question 3

Explain the difference between the short run and the long run in production.

In the short run, at least one factor of production is fixed, meaning it is too costly to change. In the long run, all factors are variable, meaning they can be changed.

In our analysis, we often assume that capital \((k)\) is fixed in the short run - it is too difficult for a firm to change the number of locations or factories that it has (capital). It can only change labor in the short run.

\[q_{SR}=f(\bar{k},l)\]

In the long run, firms can change the number of locations or factories that it has (capital), so all factors are variable.

\[q_{LR}=f(k,l)\]

Question 4

Describe, in your own words, what the law of diminishing marginal returns means. How can firms increase output

The law of diminishing returns means that adding more of one input, holding all others fixed, the marginal product of that input will diminish.

For example, if we have a fixed amount of capital (one oven), and we keep adding chefs (labor), the more chefs we add, the smaller and smaller the marginal product of labor (we get fewer and fewer additional pizzas for every chef we add). It may be such that you ultimately get negative marginal product - if you keep adding enough labor, it might actually reduce total output since there are â€œtoo many cooks in the kitchen.â€

Itâ€™s crucial to understand that this relationship consists of adding more of just one factor, and holding constant all other factors. The key problem was that there was just a single oven that we kept adding chefs to. If we want to sustainably increase our output, we need to add more of both labor and capital.

This concept is largely attributed to David Ricardo, the classical economist, who famously said that if the law of diminishing returns was not true, we would be able to grow the entire worldâ€™s food supply in a single flower pot!

Question 5

Suppose a firm can hire labor at $5/hour and rent capital for $20 per hour.

Part A

Write an equation for the total cost of the firm.

If \(w=\$5\) and \(r=20\)

\[\begin{aligned} C &= wL+rK \\ C &= 5L+20K\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part B

Suppose the firm wants to spend exactly $100. With labor on the horizontal axis and capital on the vertical axis, find the equation of the isocost line (in a graphable form), and graph it.

\[\begin{aligned} 100&=5L+20K \\ 100-5L&=20K \\ 5-0.25L&=K\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part C

If the firm is completely automated (i.e.Â it uses only capital), how many units of capital can they employ for $100?

\[\frac{C}{r}=\frac{100}{20}=5\]

Part D

If the firm uses only labor, how many units of labor can they employ for $100?

\[\frac{C}{w}=\frac{100}{5}=20\]

Part E

What is the slope of the isocost line? What does it represent?

The slope is \(0\frac{w}{r}=-\frac{5}{20}=-\frac{1}{4}\). It represents the tradeoff in the market between \(l\) and \(k\) based on their relative prices.

Part F

Suppose a tax on capital makes renting capital raises the price of capital to $25 per hour. What is the new (graphable) equation of the $100 isocost line? Graph the new isocost line on the same graph.

\[\begin{aligned} 100&=5L+25K \\ 100-5L&=25K \\ 5-0.2L&=K\\ \end{aligned}\]

An easier way is to think about the new endpoint for capital:

\[\frac{C}{r'}=\frac{100}{25}=4\]

Question 6

For each of the following production functions, identify whether the production process exhibits constant returns to scale, increasing returns to scale, or decreasing returns to scale. Be sure to show your work!

Part A

\(q=2L+4K\)

Suppose for example, we have 2 L and 2 K: \[q=2(2)+4(2)=4+8=12\]

Now we double inputs to 4L and 4K:

\[q=2(4)+4(4)=8+16=24\]

Output has doubled, from 12 to 24 units, when we have doubled inputs from 2 to 4 K & L, so we have constant returns to scale.

Part B

\(q=6L^{0.25}K^{0.75}\)

Suppose for example, we have 2 L and 2 K:

\[q=6(2)^{0.25}(2)^{0.75}=12\]

Now we double inputs to 4L and 4K:

\[q=6(4)^{0.25}(4)^{0.75}=24\]

Output has doubled, from 12 to 24 units, when we have doubled inputs from 2 to 4 K & L, so we have constant returns to scale.

Part C

\(q=2L^{0.8}K^{0.4}\)

Suppose for example, we have 2 L and 2 K:

\[q=2(2)^{0.8}(2)^{0.4}=4.59\]

Now we double inputs to 4L and 4K:

\[q=2(4)^{0.8}(4)^{0.4}=10.56\]

Output has more than doubled, from 4.59 to 10.56 units, when we have doubled inputs from 2 to 4 K & L, so we have increasing returns to scale.

Part D

\(q=2L^{0.25}K^{0.25}\)

Suppose for example, we have 2 L and 2 K:

\[q=2(2)^{0.25}(2)^{0.25}=2.82\]

Now we double inputs to 4L and 4K:

\[q=2(4)^{0.25}(4)^{0.25}=4\]

Output has less than doubled, from 2.82 to 4 units, when we have doubled inputs from 2 to 4 K & L, so we have increasing returns to scale.

Question 7

Jerryâ€™s Berries is a small farm that has the following production function for strawberries using combinations of labor \((l)\) and land \((t)\): \[q = 2 \, lt\]

The marginal products (of labor, \(l\); and land, \(t)\) are:

\[\begin{aligned} MP_l &= 2t\\ MP_t &= 2l\\ \end{aligned}\]

Put labor, \(l\) on the horizontal axis and land, \(t\) on the vertical axis.

Part A

Write an equation for \(MRTS_{l,t}\).

\[\begin{aligned} MRTS_{l,t}&=\frac{MP_l}{MP_t}\\ &=\frac{2t}{2l}\\ &=\frac{t}{l}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part B

Suppose the farm is currently using 4 units of labor and 1 unit of land. How much output (tons of strawberries) is the farm producing?

Plug this input combination into the production function:

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2 \, lt\\ q&=2(4)(1)\\ q&=8\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part C

From its current production, how much more output would the farm get by utilizing 1 more unit of labor? What about 1 more unit of land (instead of labor)?

This is measuring the marginal product of \(l\) and the marginal product of \(t\), evaluated at the firmâ€™s current input combination in production of \(l=4\) and \(t=1\).

\[\begin{aligned} MP_l&=2t\\ MP_l&=2(1)\\ MP_l&=2\\ \end{aligned}\]

Hiring one additional unit of labor, \(l\), will increase output by 2 units of strawberries.

\[\begin{aligned} MP_t&=2l\\ MP_t&=2(4)\\ MP_t&=8\\ \end{aligned}\]

Using one additional unit of land, \(t\), increase output by 8 units of strawberries.

Part D

From its current production, how many units of land would the farm be willing to forgo in order to use one more unit of labor and still produce the same output as before? How many units of labor would the farm be willing to forgo in order to use one more unit of land and still produce the same output as before?

This is measuring the marginal rate of technical substitution (i.e.Â the slope of the isoquant curve) evaluated at the firmâ€™s his current input combination of \(l=4\) and \(t=1\). From part A, we found the equation for the \(MRTS_{l,t}\):

\[\begin{aligned} MRTS_{l,t}&= \frac{t}{l}\\ MRS_{4,1}&= \frac{1}{4}\\ \end{aligned}\]

At this current input combination, the firm would give up \(\frac{1}{4}\) units of land \((t)\) to hire one more unit of labor \((l)\) to produce the same amount of output. This is the slope of the isoquant curve at this point: to go one unit to the right, we go \(\frac{1}{4}\) units down.

To use one more unit of land, \(t\), and produce the same amount of putput, the firm would give up 4 units of labor, \(l\). This is the inverse of the isoquant curve slope at this point. Consider: to go up one unit, we go 4 units to the left.

Part E

Suppose the farm can choose between input combinations of \(a = (4,1)\), \(b=(2,2)\), \(c=(2,1)\), and \(d=d(3,2)\). What outputs does each combination yield?

Check the output each input combination yields.

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2lt\\ q&=2(4)(1)\\ q&=8\\ \end{aligned}\]

Input combination \(a\) provides output of 8 units of strawberries.

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2lt\\ q&=2(2)(2)\\ q&=8\\ \end{aligned}\]

Input combination \(b\) provides output of 8 units of strawberries.

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2lt\\ q&=2(2)(1)\\ q&=4\\ \end{aligned}\]

Input combination \(c\) provides output of 4 units of strawberries.

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2lt\\ q&=2(3)(2)\\ q&=12\\ \end{aligned}\]

Input combination \(d\) provides output of 12 units of strawberries.

Part F

Sketch a graph, plotting bundles \(a, b, c\), and \(d\). Indicate any isoquant curve(s) they are on, and how much output each provides.

Question 8

Your firm builds aircraft engines using both labor (L) and power tools (K). The production function for aircraft engines is \(q=10 L^{0.5}K^{0.5}\)

Part A

Can you completely mechanize the production of aircraft engines (i.e.Â produce using all capital, no labor)?

No, if labor (L) is 0, the entire function becomes 0, yielding no output.

Part B

Suppose you currently have 100 power tools. In the short run, you cannot buy or sell power tools. Derive your short run production function.

\[\begin{aligned} q&=10\sqrt{(100)}\sqrt{L}\\ q&=10(10)\sqrt{L}\\ q&=100\sqrt{L}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part C

Find the (i) total product of labor, (ii) average product of labor, and (iii) marginal product of labor for using 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 workers.1 Round to the nearest engine. Does labor experience diminishing returns?

Simply plug in \(l=0\), \(l=1\), \(l=2 \cdots l=5\) into the production function to find the total product \((q)\). see how total product changes to find the marginal product. Divide by total output by \(l\) to find the average product:

\(l\) \(q=100\sqrt{l}\) \(MP_l=\frac{\Delta q}{\Delta l}\) \(AP_l=\frac{q}{l}\)
\(0\) \(100\sqrt{0}=0\) \(-\) \(-\)
\(1\) \(100\sqrt{1}=100\) \(100-0=100\) \(\frac{100}{1}=100\)
\(2\) \(100\sqrt{2}=141\) \(141-100=41\) \(\frac{141}{2}=71\)
\(3\) \(100\sqrt{3}=173\) \(173-141=32\) \(\frac{173}{3}=58\)
\(4\) \(100\sqrt{4}=200\) \(200-173=27\) \(\frac{200}{4}=50\)
\(5\) \(100\sqrt{5}=224\) \(224-200=24\) \(\frac{224}{5}=45\)

Yes, labor experiences diminishing returns as \(MP_l\) is decreasing as \(l\) is increasing.

Part D

Using your answer from Part C, sketch two graphs (roughly), one of total product, and one of marginal and average product, each with labor on the horizontal axis.

Part E

In the long run, does the production function exhibit constant returns to scale, increasing returns to scale, or decreasing returns to scale?

By recognizing this is a Cobb-Douglas Production function of the form \(q=Ak^{\alpha}l^{\beta}\) (here, \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are both 0.5, as \(\sqrt{x}=x^{0.5}\), we can take the shorCut of noticing that \(\alpha+\beta=1\), as \(0.5+0.5=1\), so there are constant returns to scale.

We can confirm this by hand, by plugging in a number of inputs and then increasing them at the same rate. Suppose for example, we have 2 l and 2 l:

\[q=10\sqrt{2}\sqrt{2}=10(2)=20\]

Now we double inputs to 4L and 4K:

\[q=10\sqrt{4}\sqrt{4}=10(4)=40\]

Output has doubled, from 20 to 40 units, when we have doubled inputs from 2 to 4 K & L, so we have constant returns to scale.

Question 9

Dunder Mifflin paper company produces reams of paper each week according to the production function: \[\begin{aligned}q &=10 l^{0.5} k^{0.5}\\ MP_l& = 5l^{-0.5}k^{0.5}\\ MP_k& = 5l^{0.5}k^{-0.5}\\ \end{aligned}\]

They have determined that they need to ship 1,000 reams of paper this week to Scranton, PA. Using capital costs $20, whereas labor costs $10.

Part A

What is the cost-minimizing combination of labor and capital that will yield 1,000 reams of paper? Round each to the nearest whole number.

We know that at the optimum:

\[\begin{aligned} \frac{MP_L}{MP_K}&=\frac{w}{r} && \text{Definition of optimum}\\ \frac{5L^{-0.5}K^{0.5}}{5L^{0.5}K^{-0.5}}&=\frac{10}{20} && \text{Plugging in known values}\\ L^{(-0.5-0.5)}K^{(0.5-(-0.5)}&=0.5 && \text{Exponent rule for division}\\ L^{-1}K^{1}&=0.5 && \\ \frac{K}{L}&=0.5 && \text{Exponent rule for negative exponents}\\ K&=0.5L && \text{Multiplying both sides by }L\\ \end{aligned}\]

To get exact quantities, plug this into the production function:

\[\begin{aligned} q&=10\sqrt{LK} && \text{The production function}\\ 1000 &=10\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Plugging in our function of K and } q^*=1000\\ 100 &=\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Dividing both sides by 10}\\ 100&=\sqrt{0.5L^2} && \text{Multiplying}\\ 10000&=0.5L^2 && \text{Squaring both sides}\\ 20000&=L^2 && \text{Dividing both sides by 0.5}\\ 141&\approx L && \text{Square rooting both sides}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Knowing \(L\), we can find \(K\):

\[\begin{aligned} K&=0.5L\\ K&=0.5(141)\\ K&=71\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part B

What is the total cost of using this combination of inputs?

\[\begin{aligned} wL+rK&=C\\ \$10(141)+\$20(71)&=C\\ \$1410+\$1420&=\$2830\\ \end{aligned}\]

Part C

Now suppose that they need to double their output this week, and need to produce 2,000 reams of paper. How does their optimal combination of inputs change?2

One quick hint is that recognizing the production function as a Cobb-Douglas production function and looking at the exponents on \(L\) and \(K\) (as they are square roots, the exponents are each 0.5).

\[\begin{aligned} q&=2L^{0.5}K^{0.5}\\ 1&=0.5+0.5\\ \end{aligned}\]

The sum of the exponents is 1, so the production function experiences constant returns to scale: doubling inputs will double output. We know that output doubles, so all inputs must double from about 141 workers and 71 capital to about 282 workers and 141 capital. Since the MRTS is not changing (no marginal products changed), nor did any input prices, the ratio of capital to labor used is still \(K=0.5L\).

Anyway, letâ€™s check manually. Knowing \(K=0.5L\) still, we need to find the exact quantities used in production. Plug this into the production function, as before (with double \(q\)):

\[\begin{aligned} q&=10\sqrt{LK} && \text{The production function}\\ 2000 &=10\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Plugging in our function of K and } q^*=2000\\ 200 &=\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Dividing both sides by 10}\\ 200&=\sqrt{0.5L^2} && \text{Multiplying}\\ 40000&=0.5L^2 && \text{Squaring both sides}\\ 80000&=L^2 && \text{Dividing both sides by 0.5}\\ 283&\approx L && \text{Square rooting both sides}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Knowing \(L\), we can find \(K\):

\[\begin{aligned} K&=0.5L\\ K&=0.5(283)\\ K&=141\\ \end{aligned}\]

Which we anticipated (although with rounding error on \(L\)) before.

Part E

What is the total cost of this new level of output?

\[\begin{aligned} wL+rK&=C\\ \$10(283)+\$20(141)&=C\\ \$2830+\$2800&=\$5630\\ \end{aligned}\]

It has just about doubled the cost of before, as should be intuitive (weâ€™re producing twice as much as before, with twice as many inputs at the same prices).

Part F

Suppose management at Dunder Mifflin develops a new program that magically makes everyone at the firm more productive, such that the firmâ€™s new production function becomes:

\[\begin{aligned}q &=20 l^{0.5} k^{0.5}\\ MP_l& = 10l^{-0.5}k^{0.5}\\ MP_k& = 10l^{0.5}k^{-0.5}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Still needing to supply 2,000 reams of paper this week at the same input prices, what is their new optimal combination of labor and capital?

The optimal ratio remains \(K=0.5L\). To get the new quantities, plug this into the updated production function:

\[\begin{aligned} q&=20\sqrt{LK} && \text{The new production function}\\ 2000 &=20\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Plugging in our function of K and } q^*=2000\\ 100 &=\sqrt{L(0.5L)} && \text{Dividing both sides by 10}\\ 100&=\sqrt{0.5L^2} && \text{Multiplying}\\ 10000&=0.5L^2 && \text{Squaring both sides}\\ 20000&=L^2 && \text{Dividing both sides by 0.5}\\ 141&\approx L && \text{Square rooting both sides}\\ \end{aligned}\]

Knowing \(L\), we can find \(K\):

\[\begin{aligned} K&=0.5L\\ K&=0.5(141)\\ K&=71\\ \end{aligned}\]

This is the same optimal combination as when the firm produced 1,000 copies!

Part G

How much does this combination cost? What does this show you about technological improvement (or â€œtotal factor productivityâ€)?

With the same prices of labor and capital, this is the same total cost as in part b. Notice the doubling of â€œtotal factor productivityâ€ in the production function (from 10 to 20) means the firm can use half the amount of inputs to produce the same amount as before!
